> In my humble view Rishi is not an epic phenomenon, but Rishis
> happen in modern times too with all their adapted involvements
> according to the present needs of our times.  
 
Being a rishi is indeed an epic phenomenon. Unless one has an experience, one will perhaps be unable to appreciate the possibility of such a phenomenon and understand the word rishi in a lesser light.
 
Amshas of rishis appear in modern times with elevated concentrations of purified consciousness and they may do great deeds or influence many people positively.
 
*        *        *
 
Sometimes a great person comes, does great deeds and leaves. His sishyas, partly out of their respect for guru and partly out of their own ego (isn't it great to be sishya of a "rishi"?!), start calling him a rishi.
 
The word rishi should not be a spiritual status symbol. Not being rishi is not an insult. One can be a really great person and yet not be a rishi. The word has been cheapened by people.
 
